      <p>
        The constitutional roles describe authority over the <em>company</em>. The
        operational roles describe authority over the <em>process</em>. The participant
        roles describe positions in the <em>protocol</em>. The proposed steward layer
        is accountable for the <em>schemas</em> — the bridge between all three.
      </p>

      <h2 id="domainStewards">Proposed: Domain Data Stewards</h2>

      <div class="callout callout--warn">
        <div class="callout__label">Surveying steward seat — a tier-eligibility question, not a coverage gap</div>
        <p>
          OPDA <strong>does</strong> have RICS-regulated surveying capability in membership —
          Survey Shack, plus Countrywide Surveyors (within Connells Group) and Pinnacle
          Surveyors (within MAB). What it lacks is a surveying firm at <em>Founder or Certified</em>
          tier, which the eligibility rules below require. Before the stewardship model goes live,
          the Executive Committee will need to either: (a) draw the steward from one of these
          existing member surveying firms (recruiting it to Certified if needed), (b) relax
          eligibility for under-represented contexts, or (c) deputise an external advisor
          (e.g., a RICS representative) pending that. See
          <a href="#openQuestions">Open Question 4</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p>
        Six stewards, one per primary bounded context (per
        <a href="/modelling/bounded-contexts">12-bounded-contexts</a>). Because each PDTF
        overlay belongs to exactly one bounded context, six stewards collectively cover
        every published schema artefact. The mapping:
      </p>

